                  heat. Dirty or clogged burners can reduce efficiency and
                  heating capacity.
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Draft Inducer Motor:</h3>
                <p>
                  Ensures proper venting of combustion gases out of the furnace.
                  A malfunctioning inducer motor can prevent the furnace from
                  starting.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Limit Switch:</h3>
                <p>
                  Monitors the furnace temperature and shuts off the burners if
                  the unit overheats. Helps protect the furnace from damage and
                  prevent potential fire hazards.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Gas Valve:</h3>
                <p>
                  Controls the flow of gas to the burner assembly. A faulty gas
                  valve can prevent the furnace from igniting or may cause it to
                  shut down unexpectedly.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Control Board:</h3>
                <p>
                  The brain of the furnace, managing all the electrical
                  components and ensuring they work together correctly. A
                  malfunctioning control board can cause various operational
                  issues.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Thermocouple:</h3>
                <p>
                  A safety device that senses whether the pilot light is lit and
                  shuts off the gas supply if it isn't. Commonly used in older
                  furnaces with pilot lights.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Pressure Switch:</h3>
                <p>
                  Ensures the proper airflow through the furnace. If the
                  pressure switch fails, the furnace may not operate correctly
                  or may shut down as a safety measure.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Rollout Switch:</h3>
                <p>
                  A safety switch that shuts down the furnace if flames or hot
                  gases escape from the heat exchanger. Prevents fire hazards
                  and protects the system.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Transformer:</h3>
                <p>
                  Converts the incoming electrical voltage to the appropriate
                  level needed for the furnace's components. A faulty
                  transformer can cause electrical issues and prevent the
                  furnace from operating.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Capacitor:</h3>
                <p>
                  Stores electrical energy to help start and run the blower
                  motor. A failing capacitor can lead to motor issues and
                  inefficient heating.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Fan Belt:</h3>
                <p>
                  Connects the blower motor to the fan. A worn or broken belt
                  can result in poor airflow and inefficient heating.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Thermopile:</h3>
                <p>
                  Similar to a thermocouple, but used in systems with a standing
                  pilot light to generate electrical power for the gas valve.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Condensate Pump:</h3>
                <p>
                  Used in high-efficiency furnaces to remove the water produced
                  during the heating process. A malfunctioning pump can lead to
                  water damage and reduced efficiency.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="content__page-desc">
                <h3>Flue Pipe:</h3>
                <p>
                  The duct through which combustion gases are vented outside. A
                  damaged or clogged flue pipe can cause dangerous gas leaks and
                  reduce furnace efficiency.
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                This list covers some of the most common furnace replacement
